\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 The essence of the Buddha's teachings is summed up in the Four Noble Truths of his first sermon.  The Buddha's quest was to find a way beyond personal suffering, not through reliance on dogmas, creeds or philosophies but in actual experience based in insig
ht.  He ruthlessly exposed the nature of life realising that, due to impermanence and death, life can never be apart from suffering.  This suffering arises primarily because we crave permanence, ego-enhancing credentials and safety.  To go beyond suffering
 necessitates going beyond this craving, an endeavour that demands an examination of the self.  The Buddha proclaimed:}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs21\lang2057\f5\fs21\f5\fs21 1.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 Life is suffering.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs21\lang2057\f5\fs21\f5\fs21 2.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 Suffering is due to wanting, and especially wanting the safety of permanence.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs21\lang2057\f5\fs21\f5\fs21 3.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 Suffering diminishes when this wanting is abandoned.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs21\lang2057\f5\fs21\f5\fs21 4.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 The Way is how to do it.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 The key question is what is the Way?  The Way cannot be told; it has to be experienced.  We discover the Way through meditation which in Zen is called zazen.  Through meditation we discover for ourselves that suffering is indeed due to self concern and tha
t wanting originates from the desires of the self.  In meditation we are examining the basis of this 'self'.  What sort of reality has it?}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\ul\ulc0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\b\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b Problems.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 Enquiring into the self encounters problems.  Where is it?  What is it?  Who am I?  What is a person?  We begin in infancy with bare experience and gradually we infer that there is a person who is the subject and creator of this experience.  The self is th
erefore an idea built up by the mind.  It does not have an objective existence as external things appear to have.  It is a reference point within the processes of our thought.  By solidifying into an apparent entity, the thought that creates the self becom
es the pivot around which all other thinking revolves.  The way we think determines the quality of our personal world.  In Chan we say:}
