\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs21\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs21\lang2057\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs21\lang2057\i0\b0 Deep training arises when Compassion and Insight mutually support one another.  This is then the path of the Bodhisattva - one who seeks the release of others before himself or herself.  It is the aim of the Chan practitioner to walk the path of the Bodhis
attva in whatever way it appears in one's life circumstance.  This may involve political or social activism, spreading the teachings (Dharma), social work or counselling or simply the support of anyone in need.  The essence is to assist others to their own
 realisations.  Compassion must however be directed at one's own suffering self.  Unless one is working on one's own problems any work for others is likely to be inadequately understood.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af5\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
